<font color="#FF0000">TWO DIFFERENT MEN, TWO VIEWS</font><br>
<tt>Sun Nov 16  0:38:19 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Anyone can write a book that revels all our flaws and all the things that were wrong about the Vietnam War and what is wrong with America today. <br><br>
For some reason, COL. HACKWORTH reminds me of Ron Kovic.<br><br>
“With all his many awards, Hack (COL. DAVID H. HACKWORTH, USA ARMY, RET.)still considers the Combat Infantryman Badge and the United Nations Medal for Peace -- which he was presented for his anti-nuclear work in Australia -- his &quot;highest awards.&quot;<br><br>
I consider my Combat Action Ribbon same same as the colonels Combat Infantryman Badge, my highest award. I am not so sure that I would be proud or interested in the &quot;UNEF&quot;, United Nations Medal for Peace.  Much like the Nobel Peace Prize, that was awarded to YASSER ARAFAT, NELSON MANDELA and other worthless individual that have embraced communism and terrorism. <br>
I won’t take the time here to tell you what I think of some of the United Nations or some Nobel Peace prize recipients. <br><br>
Its not the colonels that win the fight in the battle field<br>
Its not the officers that win the medals of honor among men<br>
It’s not the food, supplies or the equipment, that provides the courage, determination, and willingness to fight our country’s battle against overwhelming odds.<br><br>
It takes courage, not cowardice to win our country’s battles and that can only be found in the soldier that believes in what he is fighting for.<br><br>
We will never ever again fight battles like we did in Nam.<br>
Everyone knows that once the first bullet is fired in combat all your best-laid out plans in combat are worthless. It’s at the squad level that all the difference in the world can be made. <br><br>
The NVA were well trained, they were well discipline Communist soldiers who stood their ground and fought back. They did not lay down their arms at the first sight of American combat troops as the Iraq soldiers did. The NVA believed in their cause and they had been well trained to carry out those believes.<br><br>
In my eyes, they were Communist and I had seen the death and destruction they had reeked upon innocent South Vietnamese civilians. <br><br>
What colonel Hackworth, thinks and feels and what sells in America had nothing to do with what happened in those rice paddy fields when I was there. I was an American Soldier trained for duty, to defend my country to obey orders and to kill the enemy. Seeing what the communist soldier had done to civilians validated all the reason I ever needed for fighting Communism in South East Asia. <br><br>
Yet, the real peacekeeping mission is laid at the feet of Marines running small patrols in Sarajevo or guarding US Embasseys in checkered colored uniforms in Arab lands or other hostile nations. One mistake by anyone of them and it would crate a national crisis, alter national policy. <br>
There is where our nations national security really rests, not in books written by retired colonels, that prostitute themselves for fame and glory and a few bucks at the expense of our country's honor.<br><br>

